Due to the text limit here, I might multipost. Apologies in advance, but 4chins doesn't like testament posting.

Alright, so the initial thoughts are pretty simple so bear with me. When you have the ability to actually be able to edit, format and change text around like SF does, I feel as if you could be doing so much more, and this kind of extends into your writing as a whole in how its shaped and made. The initial segment with the alarm could have had a paragraph or two with the noise, the reaction and the explanation of the character separated with some more dynamic methods, maybe a splash of italics for the noise, a few more words giving weight to it all. As it stands, it could be much better since you aren't really doing greentext and are instead doing pseudo-prose, so a bit more development and polish could go a long way in improving how you do things.

Speaking of improving, while your writing is engaging, some sentences can at times feel a bit odd. Something like
>A quick phone call would solve your problem... Not like your co-workers already knew but you're sure they would understand
This phrase feels odd due to its location within the text. It's very quick and sudden, the first paragraph of the story after the intro to set the scene, this one continuing it, and yet it almost feels as if we are meant to know something we don't. It shouldn't be assumed your coworkers know anything from the reader when he just started reading, he has yet to gather his bearings. This feels a bit like going hard on the pity train, and while I can understand the thematics set on, this feels a bit harsh and put forwards. A more gentle easing into the setting and the situations could be done for a better result.

>She was very sweet, especially for a Saint Bernard, but proved time and time again to be a bit of a klutz.
While this may be personal preference, starting the sentence with WHAT she is tends to be better than HOW she is.

Continuing off the last sentence, people make a much better mental picture when you describe the physical first and then construct the personality. Going for something like "For a Saint Bernard, she was extremely sweet, even if proven time and time again to be a bit of a klutz" gives people the template of physical body, emotions, possible stance atributed to the emotions, with me arguing that the sentence right next to it could probably be joined to that one. You separate quite a bit of your sentences when many could be lumped together to form a more cohesive flow, but that might come in time and experience. Just keep it in mind.

Your descriptions are sometimes vague as well. How big is big? How big is she? We aren't given a frame of reference to the MP, or as to how big she is compared to him or even further compared to the scenary. You say she is plump in all the right ways later, but that is making a mental picture rather late.

>Sour milk, empty boxes, and leftovers covered the once-decent clothes and your body alongside.
I would just ditch the "and your body alongside" and make it ", alongside your body", flows much better that way.

>"Y-Yeah..." No you weren't. This was fucking terrible.
This is an example of where you could have added some formatting but didn't. Next sections you seemindly did but in this one you just decided not to, which is odd frankly. Might want to do a revision of your content as a whole, because do not take this the wrong way, a first draft is just that, you have to polish and revise it afterwards to make it first published worthy. Likely with some mistakes, but less.

>They're not in your left pocket anymore. You could've sworn you had them when you- No.
A bit of editing and more refinement could make this moment hit a lot better, a new line, maybe a "Oh god no." in italics or bold, spice it up a little, if you have the means to make people feel the dread you are writing, you should likely use them.

Wew lad, this might be a bit too much testament posting, but hopefully this will help a little.

>And that's when it hit you. For a moment, your memory vaguely saw the glint of a pair of keys making it into the dumpster.
>The only thing that made it into the damn dumpster was the keys.
"A pair of keys making it into the dumpster" into "made it into the damn dumpster" feels like some very needless repetition, even if not verbatim. Perhaps try something like:

>"And that's when it hit you. For a moment, your memory vaguely saw the glint of metal shining out as they hit the dumpster."
>"A pair of keys. The only thing that seemed to make it in."

>Between moments of standing in the shower and feeling sorry for yourself, you managed to clean up fairly nice.
Personal nitpick but clean up fairly well reads weird when you finish it like that, maybe replace it with well? Clean up fairly nice just feels not nice, if you'll pardon the joke.

> A vague memory felt like you knew the brand or had used it before. It was strange, so you shrugged it off.
This feels underdeveloped and very stately. You could do more with something like this, say the scent reminded you of it, maybe the texture felt familiar, maybe you remembered seeing it out there. Invoke the 5 senses as best as you can, even for little things, because little things can make your story hook people hard.

>No one likes to be vulnerable, but you... you despised it, keeping it locked tight.
It may be my own mistake, but this *feels* temporally inconsistent. You went from present to past, from people liking it in the now to the past of the MP and his actions. Try using liked.

>that's how wolves greet and be friendly
It's also a sign of submission (by the wolf initiating the greeting) to an acknowledged equal or higher ranking pack member.

>>37360961
>literally opened his mouth to allow it
>>37361011
>denied the friendly greeting the wolf would have left
Pretty much this. If a wolf offers to greet you like that, you want to accept it since you are telling that wolf that you like them, too, and that you are accepting them into your pack. It's not necessarily a sign of dominance to accept it if offered, but it usually signals that you are at least equal and probably higher ranking.

Refuse it and the wolf will consider that rejection and your future friendship becomes much less likely.

If you're eve in such a position, you want to push back at least a little to demonstrate a more equal ranking. So, yeah, you want to also lick the inside of their moth a little, it will make for a tighter friendship without need for either to demonstrate dominance at some point.

Some dogs will do the same thing, but it doesn't have the same strong meaning as in pack society.
